label.value: Hepatitis A Virus IgG Antibody Measurement

value.value: The determination of the amount of Hepatitis A virus IgG antibody present in a sample.
The determination of the amount of HIV-1/HIV-2 antigens and/or HIV-1/HIV-2 antibodies present in a sample.
Factors in the blood that are essential for blood coagulation. The absence or mutation of these factors can lead to hemophilia and blood clotting disorders.
The determination of the amount of JC virus DNA present in a sample.
The determination of the amount of Mumps virus IgM antibody present in a sample.
The determination of the amount of Mycoplasma pneumoniae IgA antibody present in a sample.
The determination of the amount of Mycoplasma pneumoniae IgM antibody present in a sample.
The determination of the amount of Rubella IgM antibody present in a sample.
A type of cellular proliferation assay in which bromodeoxyuridine (BrdU) is used as a substitute for thymidine in the DNA of replicating cells.

A qualitative technique used to identify specific antibodies bound to an antigen by the appearance of a precipitation band (precipitin band) formed between wells in an agar gel plate as a result of the interaction of the antigen and antibodies at optimal concentration.
A type of positron emission tomography in which labeled monoclonal antibodies are tracked and quantitated after administration to the subject.

A method used to measure testicular volume by comparing the size of one's testicles to the beads in a orchidometer, which consists of a string of 12 numbered beads of increasing sizes of 1 to 6, 8, 10, 12, 15, 20, and 25mL.

label.value: Becquerel per Gram per Kilobecquerel per Kilogram

value.value: A unit of specific radioactivity that is equal to becquerel per gram divided by dose in kilobecquerel per kilogram body weight.

A common molecular biology procedure for detection of RNA molecules.  RNA extracted from a sample was denatured and separated by slab gel electrophoresis, then blotted on to a nitrocellulose or nylon sheet and hybridized with labeled DNA or RNA that is complementary to the desired RNA, whose presence is subsequently indicated by autoradiography or other visualization techniques.

label.value: Becquerel per Milliliter per Kilobecquerel per Kilogram

value.value: A unit of specific radioactivity that is equal to becquerel per milliliter divided by dose in kilobecquerel per kilogram body weight.

label.value: Hour Times Becquerel per Gram per Kilobecquerel per Kilogram

value.value: A unit of specific radioactivity that is equal to hours times becquerel per gram divided by dose in kilobecquerel per kilogram body weight.

label.value: Hour Times Becquerel per Milliliter per Kilobecquerel per Kilogram

value.value: A unit of specific radioactivity that is equal to hours times becquerel per milliliter divided by dose in kilobecquerel per kilogram body weight.
A metric unit of volumetric radioactivity concentration defined as a concentration of a radionuclide with an activity equal to one gigabecquerel per unit volume equal to one nanoliter.
A unit of specific radioactivity used to determine the area under the curve that is equal to hours times becquerel per gram.
A unit of specific radioactivity used to determine the area under the curve that is equal to hours times becquerel per milliliter.
An assessment of the size difference in comparison to a baseline or previous value.
An indication as to whether the products of conception have been examined.
The date on which the pregnancy ended.
The exploratory purpose of the trial.

A technique for the detection of specific DNA fragments that have been separated by polyacrylamide-gel electrophoresis, transferred to a nitrocellulose or other type of paper or nylon membrane, and detected by hybridization and visualization with a labeled probe.
A unit of frequency expressed as the percentage of entities or events per second.
A dose calculation unit equal to 10 to the ninth power of the number of entities per single dose.
A unit of measure for the arithmetic mean fluorescence intensity.
A unit of measure for the geometric mean fluorescence intensity.

label.value: Milliliter per Cubic Centimeter per Minute

value.value: A unit of flow rate equal to one milliliter per cm3 per unit of time equal to one minute.
A unit of measure equal to one millisecond per one millimeter of mercury (mmHg).
A unit for the vector amount expressed as the number of vector genomes per kilogram of body weight.
A measurement of an individual's body mass index in relationship to age, in comparison to a reference percentile curve.
A measurement of an individual's height in relationship to age, in comparison to a reference percentile curve.
A measurement of an individual's weight in relationship to age, in comparison to a reference percentile curve.

A laboratory procedure for the detection or identification of proteins or peptides that have been separated by gel electrophoresis and transferred onto nitrocellulose or other type of paper or nylon membrane. The proteins are then detected by reaction with enzymatically labeled or radiolabeled antibody probes.
A measurement of an individual's weight in relationship to height, in comparison to a reference percentile curve.
An indication as to whether the radiation injury is combined with infectious, physical, thermal, and/or chemical trauma.
A description of the irradiation field as it pertains to orientation to the body and, when appropriate, the sequencing of exposure(s).

An organophosphate acetylcholinesterase inhibitor that is used as a chemical weapon. It is one of a class of binary nerve agents, called Novichok nerve agents, that was first developed by the former Soviet Union in the 1970s.

A carboxamidine compound and organophosphate acetylcholinesterase inhibitor that is used as a chemical weapon. It is one of a class of binary nerve agents, called Novichok nerve agents, that was first developed by the former Soviet Union in the 1970s.

An organophosphate acetylcholinesterase inhibitor that is used as a chemical weapon. It is one of a class of binary nerve agents, called Novichok nerve agents, that was first developed by the former Soviet Union in the 1970s.

A highly toxic protein, derived from the seeds of the rosary pea plant, that inhibits protein synthesis in exposed cells. It is characterized as a white to yellowish white powder and exposure occurs by inhalation, ingestion, or contact.

A synthetic organic thiophosphate compound and weak organophosphate acetylcholinesterase inhibitor that is used as a pesticide. It is characterized as a moderately persistent and highly soluble colorless to white solid, and exposure occurs by inhalation, contact, or ingestion.

A synthetic oxime carbamate compound and carbamate acetylcholinesterase inhibitor, endocrine disruptor, and neurotoxin that is used as a pesticide. It is characterized as a highly toxic colorless or white crystalline solid with a slightly sulfurous odor, and exposure occurs by inhalation, ingestion, or contact.

A 17-amino acid alpha3/5-conotoxin isolated from the venom of the cone snail Conus achatinus that is a competitive antagonist of the muscle-type nicotinic acetylcholine receptors, blocking synaptic transmission at the neuromuscular junction. Alpha-conotoxins are identified by a characteristic arrangement of four-cysteine residues (-CC-C-C-) and disulfide bonding of Cys1-Cys3 and Cys2-Cys4. In addition, alpha3/5-conotoxins are further classified as having three residues in the first intercysteine loop and five residues in the second intercysteine loop.
An individual's weight in kilograms divided by the square of the height in meters.

A 14-amino acid alpha3/5-conotoxin isolated from the venom of the cone snail Conus consors that is a competitive antagonist of the muscle-type nicotinic acetylcholine receptors, blocking synaptic transmission at the neuromuscular junction. Alpha-conotoxins are identified by a characteristic arrangement of four-cysteine residues (-CC-C-C-) and disulfide bonding of Cys1-Cys3 and Cys2-Cys4. In addition, alpha3/5-conotoxins are further classified as having three residues in the first intercysteine loop and five residues in the second intercysteine loop.

A 12-amino acid alpha3/5-conotoxin isolated from the venom of the cone snail Conus consors that is a competitive antagonist of the muscle-type nicotinic acetylcholine receptors, blocking synaptic transmission at the neuromuscular junction. Alpha-conotoxins are identified by a characteristic arrangement of four-cysteine residues (-CC-C-C-) and disulfide bonding of Cys1-Cys3 and Cys2-Cys4. In addition, alpha3/5-conotoxins are further classified as having three residues in the first intercysteine loop and five residues in the second intercysteine loop.

A 13-amino acid alpha-conotoxin that is isolated from the venom of the cone snail Conus geographus. It is a competitive antagonist of the muscle-type nicotinic acetylcholine receptors, blocking synaptic transmission at the neuromuscular junction. Alpha-conotoxins are identified by a characteristic arrangement of four-cysteine residues (-CC-C-C-) and disulfide bonding of Cys1-Cys3 and Cys2-Cys4.
